    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Dome for Football</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David M Graifman letter on Sept 22 article opposes moving New York Yankees to mixed-used Manhattan stadium, holding viewing would be worse for both baseball and football games</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pataki Vows to Fight Any Plan to Move Yankees to West Side'' (news article, Sept. 22):</p>
        <p>While it would certainly be a boon to sports fans to get a domed football stadium and lure the Jets or the Giants to Manhattan, stadiums designed for more than one sport are poor venues.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pataki Vows to Fight Any Plan to Move Yankees to West Side'' (news article, Sept. 22):</p>
        <p>While it would certainly be a boon to sports fans to get a domed football stadium and lure the Jets or the Giants to Manhattan, stadiums designed for more than one sport are poor venues.</p>
        <p>To accommodate the different shapes of the fields used in baseball and football, mixed-use stadiums are typically round, resulting in fans' being pushed back from the field.</p>
        <p>Shea Stadium, being round, is not a great stadium in which to watch either sport. The Meadowlands, designed for football only, and Yankee Stadium, for baseball, are great places to watch games.</p>
        <p>Moving the Yankees to a mixed-use stadium would be making the average fan's seat worse. The real beneficiary would be George Steinbrenner, who could make more money by selling luxury suites to corporations.</p>
        <p>DAVID M. GRAIFMAN  New York, Sept. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
